Music and Circadian Rhythms Experiment Consent Form

Purpose 

You are being asked to be a volunteer in a research study. The purpose of this study is to better understand the relation between music perceptions and the circadian rhythms among listeners of different cultures. 

 

Ethics

This study has been reviewed by the Georgia Tech Institutional Review Board (IRB), and has been identified as â€œMinimal risk research under 45 CFR 46. (Protocol 21153). This study contains neither any personal benefits nor any known risks to you. 

 

Duration 

The survey should take approximately 15 - 20 minutes to complete. Your answers are extremely valuable to us and we thank you for participating in this survey. 

 

Confidentiality 

The study data will be collected anonymously. Data obtained though this survey will only be connected to your anonymous identity through Qualtrics and will be securely stored on a password-protected and encrypted computer for a minimum of 5 years as per Georgia Tech policy. In any final published version of this research, the identity of survey participants will not be disclosed. We will comply with any applicable laws and regulations regarding confidentiality. To make sure that this research is being carried out in the proper way, the Georgia Institute of Technology IRB may review study records. The Office of Human Research Protections may also look at study records. 

 

Rights

Your participation in this study is voluntary. You may refuse or discontinue your voluntary participation in this research study at any time. You do not waive any of your legal rights by agreeing to be in the study. 

 

Contacts and Questions

For questions, concerns, or complaints about the study, you may contact the P.I., Dr. Claire Arthur at: claire.arthur[at]gatech.edu or Rhythm Jain at: rjain354[at]gatech.edu. If you have any questions about your rights as a research subject, you may contact Ms. Melanie Clark, Georgia Institute of Technology at melanie.clark[at]oria.gatech.edu or by phone at (404) 894-6942.
